## Page 2 — Status Tracker
### *"Here is where we are right now."*

**The Moment**
This is the recurring operational surface. It lives in the weekly team meeting, the Monday morning check-in, the founder's Friday review. It is designed to be opened, reviewed, updated, and closed — probably in fifteen minutes or less. It is not a page to linger on. It is a page to move through.

It is also the primary input mechanism for the rest of the execution layer. Every status update made here feeds the momentum synthesis, the wind-down, and the retrospective. The more honest and current the data in this view, the more meaningful everything downstream becomes.

**What the Page Needs to Do**
Give a clear, filterable view of every milestone in the sprint — who owns it, what status it is in, when it is targeted. Make updating a status fast enough to do live in a meeting. Surface blockers and dependencies clearly so the team can address them in real time.

**The Story It Tells**
Here is the full plan, in motion. Here is who is doing what. Here is what is complete, what is in flight, and what has not started yet. Here is what is at risk.

The story on this page is not about analysis — it is about ground truth. At any moment in the quarter, this page should be an accurate reflection of where the sprint actually stands.

**What Information Is on the Page**

*Deterministic — pulled from the sprint record and milestone status:*
- Every milestone across all initiatives, grouped by initiative with the parent initiative and capability area shown
- Status per milestone: Not Started, In Progress, Complete, Blocked
- Owner per milestone
- Target month
- Notes field per milestone — free text, updated by anyone with access
- Summary bar: overall milestone completion percentage, count of milestones by status, days remaining in sprint
- Sprint goal banner — persistent at the top, always visible
- Filter controls: by 3P column, by initiative, by owner, by status, by timeframe

*No AI on this page.*
This is a deterministic surface entirely. The goal is speed and accuracy. AI synthesis belongs on other pages. Here, the founder needs facts, not interpretation.

**How AI Is Used**
Not used on this page. This is an intentional design decision — the status tracker is a human-driven tool. Founders and team members update it. The data they enter here feeds AI synthesis elsewhere. Introducing AI interpretation on this surface would slow it down and reduce trust in the underlying data.

**The Emotional Target**
The founder should feel in control. Not overwhelmed by the volume of work, but grounded — they can see the full picture and make quick, informed decisions about where to direct attention. The team should feel seen — their work is visible, their progress is acknowledged, their blockers have a place to live.

