## Page 4 — Sprint Wind-Down
### *"Here is how we close this chapter and prepare for the next one."*

**The Moment**
This page becomes relevant in the final two to three weeks of the quarter. It is not triggered automatically — it surfaces contextually, either as a prompt in the navigation or as a suggestion on the execution overview page: *"You have 18 days remaining in Q1. It may be time to begin your wind-down review."*

Wind-down is a distinct and important moment. It is the bridge between execution and the next planning cycle. It helps the founder make intentional decisions about what to close, what to carry forward, and what to release — rather than letting the quarter simply expire and rolling everything over by default.

This page also begins seeding the retrospective. The honest reflection that happens during wind-down feeds the retrospective synthesis and the forward guidance for next quarter's planning.

**What the Page Needs to Do**
Help the founder make three types of intentional decisions before the sprint closes:

One — completion decisions: which incomplete initiatives and milestones are realistically completable in the remaining time, and which are not. The founder marks each one: Complete by end of sprint / Roll over to next sprint / Release — no longer relevant.

Two — rollover preparation: for items being rolled over, prompt a brief reflection. Was this deprioritized intentionally or did something get in the way? Does it belong in Prioritize next quarter or can it move to Plant? This reflection feeds the Quarter Map for the next sprint cycle.

Three — forward seeding: two or three prompted questions that help the founder begin thinking about next quarter before they close this one. Not a planning session — just an orientation. "What surprised you most about this quarter?" "What capability area needs more attention than you gave it?" "What would you classify differently if you were starting over?"

**The Story It Tells**
Here is what this quarter actually contained. Here is what we are choosing to carry forward intentionally. Here is what we are releasing. And here is the very beginning of a thought about what comes next.

The story on this page is about agency and intentionality — the founder is not letting the quarter happen to them. They are choosing how it ends.

**What Information Is on the Page**

*Deterministic — pulled from sprint record and current status:*
- All incomplete initiatives and milestones, grouped by 3P bucket
- Days remaining in sprint
- Owner of each incomplete item
- Original success definition for each incomplete initiative (so the founder can make an informed keep/release decision)

*Human-generated — founder input:*
- Completion decision per incomplete item (Complete / Roll Over / Release)
- Reflection note per rolled-over item (optional but prompted)
- Answers to the three forward-seeding questions

*AI-generated — light synthesis:*
- A brief summary of the wind-down decisions made, formatted for the founder's review before the sprint formally closes. Not interpretive — just a clean reflection of the choices made: "You are carrying forward X initiatives into next quarter, releasing Y, and targeting Z for completion in the remaining time."
- The forward-seeding answers are stored and passed forward as context into the next quarter's planning flow — so when the founder opens the Quarter Map for Q2, the platform already has a sense of what they learned from Q1.

**How AI Is Used**
Lightly on this page. The heavy AI work happens in the retrospective. Here, AI is used primarily to summarize and organize the founder's decisions, and to pass the forward-seeding answers forward into the next planning cycle's context. The founder's voice dominates this page — AI is the scribe, not the narrator.

**The Emotional Target**
The founder should feel the satisfaction of deliberate closure — not the anxiety of an unfinished sprint. They are not failing at what remains incomplete. They are making intentional choices about what matters enough to carry forward and what has served its purpose. The quarter ends with agency, not with a list of things that didn't get done.

